  "prompt": "What mean by alkali?",
  "response": "The term \"alkali\" refers to a class of **basic (as opposed to acidic)** substances that are soluble in water and capable of neutralizing acids. Alkalis are typically characterized by their **bitter taste**, **slippery feel**, and their ability to turn **red litmus paper blue**.\n\n### Key Features of Alkalis:\n1. **pH Level**: Alkalis have a **pH greater than 7**, making them the opposite of acids, which have a pH less than 7.\n2. **Hydroxide Ions**: Alkalis release **hydroxide ions (OH\u207b)** when dissolved in water, which is why they are also referred to as **bases**.\n3. **Neutralization**: They react with acids to form **salt and water** in a process called **neutralization**.\n   - Example: \\( \\text{HCl (acid)} + \\text{NaOH (alkali)} \\rightarrow \\text{NaCl (salt)} + \\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\)\n4. **Common Examples**: Sodium hydroxide (NaOH), potassium hydroxide (KOH), and calcium hydroxide (Ca(OH)\u2082) are common alkalis.\n5. **Uses**: Alkalis are used in various applications, including soap making, cleaning products, and chemical manufacturing.\n\nIn summary, an **alkali** is a water-soluble base that neutralizes acids, has a high pH, and releases hydroxide ions in solution.",
